```python
def is_prime(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return False
    elif n <= 3:
        return True
    elif n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:
        return False
    i = 5
    while i * i <= n:
        if n % i == 0 or n % (i + 2) == 0:
            return False
        i += 6
    return True
```
This function works by first checking if the number is less than or equal to 1, in which case it is not prime. If the number is 2 or 3, it is prime. For larger numbers, it then checks divisibility by 2 or 3. If the number is not divisible by 2 or 3, it then checks all potential divisors from 5 up to the square root of the number. If it finds a divisor, the number is not prime. If it doesn't find a divisor, the number is prime.

In LaTeX, the generation of a table of contents can be automatically done through the use of certain commands. First, you must use the `\tableofcontents` command where you want your table of contents to appear, typically after the abstract or summary of your document.

Then, LaTeX will use the information from your document's sections, subsections, and so on to generate the table of contents.

Here is an example of how a basic LaTeX document with these commands might look:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\title{My Document}
\author{Your Name}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
This is a simple example of a document with a table of contents.
\end{abstract}

\tableofcontents

\newpage

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Main Body}
This is the main body.

\subsection{Subsection One}
This is the first subsection of the main body.

\subsection{Subsection Two}
This is the second subsection of the main body.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\section{}` and `\subsection{}` commands are used to create sections and subsections in the document. The `\tableofcontents` command is used to insert a table of contents at the beginning of the document. The table of contents will list all the sections and subsections along with their page numbers.

Note: LaTeX uses the most recent run of your document to generate the table of contents, so you may need to run your document twice to get an updated table of contents after adding or changing sections.

To represent a chess board state in LaTeX using FEN notation, you can use the `skak` and `xskak` packages, which are designed for typesetting chess games. Here is an example of a LaTeX code that includes all the required commands and packages.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\newchessgame
\setchessboard{showmover=false}

% Here, replace the FEN string with your own
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\chessboard

\end{document}
```

The `xskak` package is a extension of the `skak` package and provides additional commands to typeset chess games. The `chessboard` package provides the command to draw the board.

Remember to replace the FEN string in the `\fenboard` command with your own FEN string. 

The 'w' in the FEN string indicates it's white's move, 'KQkq' refers to the castling availability (K = white can castle kingside, Q = white can castle queenside, k = black can castle kingside, q = black can castle queenside), the '-' indicates no square is available for en passant, and '0 1' is the halfmove clock and fullmove number respectively. 

Please ensure to compile the document with PDFLaTeX, as the `skak` package uses PostScript for drawing, which is not supported by all LaTeX compilers.

